The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Orient Paper and Industries Ltd has reported a 506 per cent jump in profit after tax at Rs 130.68 crore for 2006-07. Net sales of the company grew 29 per cent to Rs 1,097 crore. A company spokesman said the three divisions of the company cement, paper and fan had done well during the period. Orient paper has announced a dividend of 100 per cent for 2006-07.

 Haldia Petrochemicals Ltds short-term borrowing programme of Rs 100 crore has received an A+ credit rating from Icra. The rating denotes highest credit quality with lowest credit risk and also takes into consideration improved financial performance, liquidity position and higher tolling margin.

 The Reserve Bank has said foreign institutional investors cannot purchase shares in Sesa Goa Ltd without its permission, as the company has hit the FII limit of 22 per cent of its paid-up capital. 

 Sterlite Optical Technologies has posted a net profit of Rs 19.32 crore for the quarter ended March 31 against Rs 22.40 crore in the year-ago period. Total income of the company was Rs 387.99 crore compared with Rs 146.63 crore.

 IOCs Gujarat Refinery recorded a crude throughput of 12.95 mt in 2006-07 and its diesel production was at 5.06 mt. The distillate yield was 71.7 per cent of crude, the highest since the implementation of BS-II and Euro-III HSD specifications.

 East Coast Railway has witnessed a growth in its freight loading and passenger transport in the last 11 months of 2006-07. It carried 46.70 million passengers and loaded 75.32 mt of freight. The railway division earned Rs 4.166.65 crore during the fiscal.

 MindTree Consulting Ltd has clocked a 66.1 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 90.05 crore in the year ended March 31, 2007 against Rs 54.21 crore in the previous fiscal. Revenues increased 31.5 per cent to Rs 590.35 crore from Rs 448.80 crore in the year-ago period.

 Satyam Computer Services Ltd has entered into a pact with Temenos, a Switzerland-based integrated core banking systems provider. Satyam will implement T24, Temenos modular core banking system.

 Sandvik Coromant has launched 1,650 products under its CoroPak range. The products will cater to the automotive, aerospace and general engineering sectors.

 Shree Cement Ltd has launched Tuff Cement 3556. The company has set up a 1.5-million-tonne unit in Rass, Rajasthan, to manufacture the brand.

